<br>
When a pet's movement mode is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sit</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it will not move from its current location in response to a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet back off</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet hold</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and enemies will likely soon add themselves to the pet's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  However, if a pet's movement mode is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Follow</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Guard</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet back off</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or especially <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet hold</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will cause the pet to attempt to withdraw from combat to either its owner or its guard point, generally making it easier to select its next target with less interference.<br>
<br>
The macro <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet hold, /pet back off</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be useful, as it first causes the pet to ignore its <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and then empties it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monster Summoning</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets do not cast, and so can be easier to control, as the only way they can get on an enemy's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hate List</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is by meleeing.  A meandering <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monster</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pet thus gives a longer interval for the owner to call it off, and avoid inadvertent aggroing.<br>
<br>
