<br>
I havent used this command in awhile, but back when I did use it it would cancel whatever the current command was and return the pet to the state it was in previous to that command being issued. Typically it just works like /pet back off (pet is attacking, /pet as you were, it returns to its previous state of /pet guard or /pet sit) but it would also tell a /pet guard here to resume /pet follow and would tell a following pet to resume /pet guard (assuming those were the previous commands). Makes for a useful toggle type switch at times.<br>
<br>
An additional note - the reason it seems like /pet as you were acts like /pet back off then /pet sit is because the commands are actually getting reissued, not returning to a previous state. Thus if you had your pet on guard and told it to attack, /pet as you were will cancel the attack command (thus the /pet back off) and re-issue the guard command *but at the new pet location* (thus the similarity to /pet sit). If you then play with the pet normally, you will notice it returns to that spot and doesnt sit at new locations, thus confirming it is /pet guard and not /pet sit.<br>
<br>
YMMV, I havent used it in probably over a year, so Verant could very well have buggered it since then. I'd be curious to see if it would return a pet to /pet hold after you tell it to attack or if the pet would just go back to guard (I dont have /pet hold yet)<br>
